Introduction

What are various ways to predict the outcome of NFL games? In this project, we will examine the outcomes of NFL games by focusing on weather factors, including temperature and humidity, location, quarterback performance, and point differences in intradivisional games. There are many complexities that factor into NFL games and teams' performances, so we will investigate some of those factors.

Description of games.csv and variables:

Games.csv is a dataset including game data from the 2013 regular NFL season with data about where the game was played, the final score, the date, and the weather. Variables used from games.csv include home_abb (home team abbreviation), home_score, away_score, humidity (average percent humidity at the game) and temperature (average temperature at the game in Farenheit).

Description of plays.csv and variables:

plays.csv is a dataset which includes play-by-play data from NFL games played during the 2013 NFL season. The data included involves variables describing everything that occurred throughout the game. Relevant variables used are posteam which describes the team with possession of the ball, play_type, and passer_player_name/rusher_player_name which gives us the name of the players who passed or ran the ball on any given play.

For games.csv, the data is already tidy as it is. Each column represents a unique variable. The only part that was not tidy is the humidity variable which was not an integer value and had the % symbol. The following characteristics held of the data that made the dataset tidy: each row represents an observation, each column represents a variable, each value gets its own cell, each different type of data set gets its own table.

Question 1: What impact does weather have on points scored by game?

A: What is the relationship between total points scored by game and the temperature?

For this question, we will start by using linear regression to see whether there is a relationship between total points scored (by game) and the temperature. Particularly when it is hot (and humid) outside, it becomes more difficult for the body to sweat and cool itself down during exercise, so we would hypothesize that hotter temperatures correspond with lower game point totals. The relationship, if at all, is anticipated to be minimal as many factors go into a game's total score, including injuries, team ratings, individual players overall wellbeing, and countless others. Additionally, especially at the pro-athlete level, athletes may be conditioned and trained to play in various weather conditions. Finally, although dome stadium games have been filtered out, outdoor football stadiums may still also lessen the effects of harsher weather.

In [157]:
# Filtering out the games played in dome stadiums and creating variable total points:
total_pts <- games %>% filter(home_abb != "DET", home_abb != "NO", home_abb != "ARI", home_abb != "IND",
                            home_abb != "MIN", home_abb != "SD", home_abb != "STL", temperature !=0) %>%
    mutate(total_points = home_score + away_score)
# Creating the linear regression model:
total_mdl <- lm(total_points ~ temperature, data = total_pts)
summary(total_mdl)

The above graph of the actual data against the model confirms that although the relationship might be weak, there does appear to be on average slightly less points scored when it is hotter outside, with a predicted 15 point difference between the coldest and hottest games.

B: Does temperature have a greater impact on total points scored around the U.S.?

Hotter temperatures around the U.S. manifest differently. Particularly in the West, hotter temperatures correspond to drier conditions while in the Midwest, South, and Northeast, hotter temperatures usually mean humid conditions. Additionally, by personal experience, regions like the Midwest and Northeast have some of the greatest variability in temperatures in the country.

The West also tends to be the most moderate of temperatures during the NFL season with only a handful of games above 75 degrees and all but one game above freezing.

C: What role does humidity play in predicting scores?

Focusing on the different regions pointed us to question the impact of humidity in addition to the impact of hot temperatures on point totals of each game.

Overall, although the effect of weather on point totals is small, it doesn't appear completely negligible. Especially in more extreme hot and humid conditions, point totals tend to be lower. As stated before though, weather is all but one outside influence that could predict game point totals and doesn't take into account the effect of quality of offense or defense of either team, and weather alone certainly cannot predict total points by game. These questions are also limited by a relatively small sample size of n = 185 games played in outdoor stadiums during the 2013 NFL season, with only n = 71 games at or above 65 to compare hot and humid conditions with humidity versus point totals. A potential improvement to this question could be to account for the quality of team and calculating whether they score above or below their season average, as well as including data from more NFL seasons.

Question 3: Should I Stay or Should I Throw?

Overview

Quarterback is arguably the most important position in all of football. The quarterback is often the heart and soul of a team and the team's success is highly dependent on how well the Quarterback plays. Quarterbacks have to make decisions to throw the ball or run the ball and these are very crucial decisions that often dictate the outcomes of games. Some Quarterbacks are better than others in specific areas and the aim of this section is to explore how the decision to run or throw impacts team success.

SubQuestion 1: Which Quarterbacks Perform Better than Others Overall?

QB Rating is one of the key indicators for how well a quartberback is performing and is a great statistic to quickly identify better players. I will be using the formula for QB rating used universally throughout football to identify superior quarterbacks which will help with my overall analysis. I will the create a scatterplot of QB ratings to help us visualize the players and their respective statistics. We need to do this because the scatterplot alows us to easily pickout Quarterbacks and rapidly analyze their performance in comparison to the rest of the league

In [139]:
QB.Rating = plays %>%
  filter(play_type == "pass") %>%
  mutate(QB.team = paste(passer_player_name,posteam, sep = " ")) %>%
  group_by(QB.team, posteam) %>%
  summarize(Games.Played = n_distinct(game_date),
                Total.Passes = n(),
                Completed = length(air_yards != 0),
                Incomplete = length(air_yards == 0),
                Completion.Rate = round(Completed/Total.Passes,3)*100,
                Total.Yards = sum(yards_gained),
                Yards.per.Att = sum(yards_gained)/Total.Passes,
                Interceptions = sum(interception),
                Interceptions.per.att = round(Interceptions/Total.Passes,3)*100,
                TDs = sum(touchdown),

QB.Rusher = plays %>%
  filter(play_type == "run") %>%
  mutate(QB.team = paste(rusher_player_name, posteam, sep=" ")) %>%
  group_by(QB.team, posteam) %>%
  summarise(Games.Played = n_distinct(game_date),
                Total.Runs = n(),
                Total.Yards = sum(yards_gained),
                Fumbles = sum(fumble),
                Runs.per.Game = Total.Runs/Games.Played,
                Fumbles.per.Yard = round(Fumbles/Total.Yards*100,3),
                Yards.per.Att = sum(yards_gained)/Total.Runs,
                TDs = sum(touchdown),
                TDs.per.100 = round(TDs/Total.Runs,3)*100) %>%
  filter(QB.team %in% starters_team) %>%
  arrange(posteam)

Fumbling and its effect

Fumbles are a huge part of the game of football. They can cause momentum shifts and cause game altering moments that dictate who wins a game. As a quarterback, fumbles are your worst nightmare and impact your team negatively. Here, my goal is to use ggplot to create a scatterplot of the quarterbacks who rushed the ball and analyze their rush yards along with the fumbles they lost. This is a good indicator of whether a quarterback is capable of running effectively and if they should continue, or rather stick to throwing the ball. Finally, we only want to look at QB's who ran the ball over 2 times per game as that shows a tendency in their game rather than running by chance

Conclusion

After performing all the data analyis above, we can see that rushing quarterbacks have an advantage over solely pocket passing quarterbacks as they add an additional dimension to the offense and create more opportunities for their team. This is indicative because successful rushing quarterbacks which we have identified from abive such as Seattle's Russell Wilson, Carolina's Cam Newton, and San Francisco's Colin Kaepernick all led their teams deep into the postseason that year. Additionally, although these quarterbacks may have slightly lower QB Ratings (which we calculated in the first part) in comparison to the rest of the league, this is because rushing the football involves higher risk as a quarterback. Since QB Rating is a holistic measure of a quarterback's performance, the statistics may be negatively impacted by running the ball, however, overall we see that this leads to increased team success.

To start making inferences, the winning team in each of the eight divisions for the 2013 NFL Regular Season was selected for analysis. Columns that were not relevant to this question were removed (also for consolidation purposes), which is why the columms "game_url", "state_of_game","weather", "wind_mph, "wind_chill", "game_id", "humidity", "id","week" and "temperature" were removed. The columns "type" and "season" were also removed because it has become evident that all of the rows in the dataset were collected from the 2013 NFL Regular season. Below is the list of each division and the respective division leaders:

AFC East: New England Patriots (NE)// AFC West: Denver Broncos (DEN)// AFC North: Cincinnati Bengals (CIN) // AFC South: Indianapolis Colts (IND) //

NFC East: Philadelphia Eagles (PHI)// NFC West: Seattle Seahawks (SEA) // NFC North: Green Bay Packers (GB) // NFC South: Carolina Panthers (CAR)

It is important to note that each division has 4 teams, so each team will play the three other teams in their respective division exactly twice during the regular season. For this question, we will examine the games where the division leaders played the other teams in their division, with a total of six games for each division due to the fact that they played each team twice. The "selected_games" subset will allow us to examine the games that the division winners play against their other divisional opponents.

Two new columns were created using the mutate function to denote the divisional winning team and the opposing divisional team, called "divisional_winner and "divisional_opponent", respectively. Additionally, a column titled "divisional_winner_score" and a column named "opponent_score" were created to make point difference analysis easier.

A. Can we see any similarities in point differences for teams that have played each other twice across the two games?

Due to the fact that we are examining the difference in points between the divisional champion team and their respective opponent, we will use the mutate function to create a new column called "point_difference." It is expected that there will be both positive and negative values in this column, where positive values indicate that the divisional champion won the game and a negative value indicates that the opponent had beaten the divisional champion in the game.

The mutate function was also used to create a new column called "net_point_difference", which calculates the sum of the point differences for the two games that each divisional winning team played against their divisional opponents.

In [115]:
new_games <- selected_games  %>% arrange(divisional_winner, divisional_opponent) %>%
mutate(division_winner_score = as.integer(division_winner_score)) %>% 
mutate(opponent_score = as.integer(opponent_score)) %>%
mutate(point_difference = division_winner_score - opponent_score) %>% 
mutate(point_difference = as.integer(point_difference)) %>% group_by(divisional_opponent) %>% 
mutate(net_point_difference = sum(point_difference)) %>% 
select(divisional_winner, divisional_opponent,date, division_winner_score, 
       opponent_score, point_difference, net_point_difference)

The scatterplot is color-coded, in which each opponent team has a distinct color. In [155]:
ggplot(data = new_games) +

It appears that the point difference between the two games is pretty random, and there have been many cases where the divisional winning team had beaten their divisional opponent in one game and lost to their opponent in the next game, or vice versa. The scatterplots illustrate that there is a large variation between the point differences, and not many similarities in the point difference value or magnitude.

B. Do the net point differences play a role in the playoff rankings? (are there any similarities between point differences for wild card teams?)

For data visualization, a bar graph was created to observe the net point difference between the divisional winning team and their divisional opponents. Each division had one winner, and this winner played against the three other teams in their division twice. Teams that the divisional winner played that had a large positive net point difference showed to be weaker opponents, and teams that the divisional winner palyed that had a large negative net point difference showed to be stronger opponents. It will be interesting to see if any of the opposing teams to show a negative net point difference were one of the "wild card" teams. The wild card teams are seeded fifth and sixth in their respective conference for the playoffs, meaning that these teams were seeded behind the winners of their division but still had a chance to play in the playoffs. Rankings for the playoffs are based on the total number of wins during the regular season, so the number of points that a team wins or loses by does not really have an impact on this. However, we will still be able to see if any opponent teams that show a negative value for net point difference were one of the wild card teams.

We would expect that the wild card teams to have either a negative net point difference or a positive point difference of small magnitude, which could explain that the games were close in final scores.

In [123]:
ggplot(data = new_games) + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = divisional_winner, fill = divisional_opponent, 
y= net_point_difference), position = "dodge", stat = "identity")  +
ggtitle("Net Point Difference between Divisional Winner Teams and their Divisional Opponents") + 
labs(x = "Divisional Winner", y = " Net Point Difference")

A scatterplot was also created to visualize the net point difference against each team.

In [153]:
ggplot(data = new_games) + geom_point(mapping = aes(x = divisional_winner, y = net_point_difference)) + 
facet_wrap(divisional_winner~divisional_opponent) + 
ggtitle("Scatterplot of Net Point Differences Between Divisional Champions and their Divisional Opponents") +
labs(x = "Divisional Winner", y = " Net Point Difference")

Based on the graph above, it appears that the following teams had a negative net point difference between their divisional opponents: Carolina Panthers vs. New Orleans Saints, Green Bay Packers vs. Chicago Bears, Green Bay Packers vs. Detroit Lions, and Philadelphia Eagles vs. Dallas Cowboys.

In the 2013 NFL Regular Season, the wild card teams for the NFC Playoffs were the San Francisco 49ers and the New Orleans Saints. The wild card teams for the AFC playoffs were the Kansas City Chiefs and the San Diego Chargers. The only wild card team that showed a negative value for net point difference against their divisional-winning-opponent was the New Orleans Saints, but it should be noted that the San Diego Chargers had a net point difference of only 1 against the Denver Broncos, the winner of their division. The net point difference between the Kansas City Chiefs and the Denver Broncos was 17, and the net point difference between the San Francisco 49ers and the Seattle Seahawks was 24. Both of these point differences are quite large, and neither are negative as we predicted. Therefore, it does not appear that net point difference has an impact on playoff rankings.

Conclusion

During the regular season, the four teams in each division will play their three other divisional opponents exactly twice. In summary, there is large variability in the point difference between the teams in each game, and it does not appear that the point differences can be predicted due to the fact that many teams have one the first game against their opponent and lost to the same opponent in their second game. There are many factors that can influence the number of points scored, including weather, injuries, and location (home vs. away field). The net point difference between the two games was calculated and visualized, which showed that stronger opponents had large, negative net point differences against their division leaders and weaker opponents had large, positive net point differences against their division leaders.

General Conclusion for Project

In conclusion, based on the data and the questions analyzed above, we are able to see how there are many different factors that impact the outcomes of games which would be hard for the casual fan to identify. Furthermore, we were able to make inferences based on the point difference between each division-leading team and their divisional opponents in the games that they played twice in the season. Finally, we identified the importance of rushing and passing ability possessed by quarterbacks and how their performance impacts team wins. Overall, this data set allowed us to explore various factors which are ingrained in the intricacies of the NFL and better understand games and their outcomes as a whole.
